ref><ref name=SBS>http://www.scmp.com/article/461488/bauhinia-honours-citys-sars-heroes</ref> (born 28 August 1947), is a [[diva]], actress and [[Master of Ceremonies|MC]] from Hong Kong. She is a personality in Chinese-speaking communities. She has been nicknamed \"The Big Sister\" in the HK entertainment circle.<ref name=\"xinhua1\">Xinhuanet. \"[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-12/31/content_7343134.htm Xinhuanet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219101548/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-12/31/content_7343134.htm |date=2008-02-19 }}\".\n''Fans jam-pack Liza Wang's free concert.'' Retrieved on 10 March 2008.</ref> Wang was a delegate in the [[National People's Congress]] from 1988 to 1997, and she is a member of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]].<ref name=\"cityu\">Cityu.edu.hk \"[http://www6.cityu.edu.hk/puo/CityUMember/Story/StoryChi.aspx?id=20070830141651 Cityu.edu.hk] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080112015716/http://www6.cityu.edu.hk/puo/CityUMember/Story/StoryChi.aspx?id=20070830141651 |date=2008-01-12 }}\". ''\u57ce\u5927\u5c07\u9812\u6388\u69ae\u8b7d\u535a\u58eb\u5b78\u4f4d\u4e88\u56db\u4f4d\u9818\u8896.'' Retrieved on 10 March 2008.</ref>\n\n==Entertainment career==\nLiza Wang was born on 28 August 1947 in Sheunghai, She moved to Hong Kong from Shanghai in autumn 1956 and signed up for Rediffusion Hong Kong's first Artist Academy class in 1967. From thousands of applicants, the 20-year-old Liza was one of the nine that were picked to attend acting classes. She was also the first to graduate from the academy.\n\n===Television===\nHer career has spanned four decades, since 1967. She began working for Rediffusion Television Limited (later renamed [[Asia Television]] and now defunct) until she joined TVB in 1971. She was one of the members of the all-girl music group [[Four Golden Flowers]].<ref>[[Television Broadcasts Limited]] TVB \u2013 Lydia Shum exclusive \u2013 \u6771\u5f35\u897f\u671b\u4e4b\u6c38\u6046\u7684\u958b\u5fc3\u679c \u2013 \u80a5\u59d0 \u2013 21 Feb 2008.</ref> Wang initially made her mark in the entertainment industry in drama series. Her work in front of the camera was followed by that behind the scenes on television productions.\n\nIn 2005, she received the Best Actress award during TVB's 38th Anniversary. She received this award the second time for her role in ''[[Wars of In-laws]]''. Wang received her first Best Actress award for her drama series ''[[The Awakening Story]]'' in 2001. She celebrated her 40th anniversary in the entertainment industry in 2007.\n\n===Singing career===\nIn parallel with her acting career Wang had a successful singing career, based on albums for her television series, consisting of TV theme songs.  She has sung [[cantopop]] as well as [[mandopop]]. She performed duets with singer [[Adam Cheng]]. She continues to perform TV theme songs such as \"\u6771\u65b9\u4e4b\u73e0\" for musical series like the 2006 [[Glittering Days (TV series)|Glittering Days]].<ref>First for Music News. \"[http://www.nme.com/video/search/%E6%B1%AA%E6%98%8E%E8%8D%83 NME]\". ''Liza Wang videos''. Retrieved 10 March 2008.</ref>\n\n===Cantonese opera===\nShe experimented with stage musicals before becoming a [[Cantonese opera]] actress. It was within the Cantonese opera community that Wang met her longtime partner, [[Law Kar-ying]]. In 2005 the [[Sunbeam Theatre]] in [[North Point]], Hong Kong's only regular venue for Cantonese Opera performances, was planned to close following a change of ownership.<ref name=\"cityu\" /> Wang decided to negotiate with the new owner, who then promised to extend the contract with the Cantonese Opera groups. Wang then criticized the Government for its lack of support for Cantonese Opera, and the Government promised to adopt Wang's request.\n\nWang was Chairman of the [[Chinese Artist Association of Hong Kong]] (\u9999\u6e2f\u516b\u548c\u6703\u9928) from 1992 to 1997, then again from 2005 to 2009.<ref name=\"cityu\" /> In 2007 Wang was awarded the '''Montblanc de la Culture Arts Patronage Award'''.<ref name=\"cityu\" /> She was later awarded an Honorary Doctorate of Letters by the [[City University of Hong Kong]].\n\nIn February 2009 Wang fought for the development rights to restore the [[North Kowloon Magistracy]] building (\u5317\u4e5d\u9f8d\u88c1\u5224\u6cd5\u9662) in [[Sham Shui Po]].<ref name=\"stan1\">The Standard HK. \"[http://abc.html The Standard.com]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\". ''http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=30&art_id=78355&sid=22755290&con_type=3.''{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Retrieved on 13 March 2009.</ref> The building was originally proposed to be a new [[Cantonese opera]] training and performance center. Hong Kong's government granted the bid to the US [[Savannah College of Art and Design]].<ref name=\"stan1\" /> Wang was upset over the loss, and said the government was only paying lip service to causes such as Cantonese opera.  The magistracy building is to be turned into a school specializing in creative and [[digital media]].<ref name=\"stan1\" /><ref>\"[http://hk.news.yahoo.com/article/090217/3/aqmm.html Yahoo]\". ''\u516b\u548c\u843d\u9078 \u6c6a\u660e\u8343\u8f5f\u9ed1\u7bb1\u4f5c\u696d'' Retrieved on 13 March 2009</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Pan-democrat home return permits request===\nSince the [[Transfer of the sovereignty of Hong Kong|1997 transfer of sovereignty]], the [[Communist Party of China]] have banned 8 of the 25 Hong Kong [[pro-democracy|pan-democrat]] [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|legislative councilors]]. They are barred from the mainland except for tours organized by the government.<ref>Scmp. \"[http://www.scmp.com/portal/site/SCMP/menuitem.2af62ecb329d3d7733492d9253a0a0a0/?vgnextoid=d5bafb2748f78110VgnVCM100000360a0a0aRCRD&ss=Hong+Kong&s=News Scmp]\". ''End democrats' travel ban, delegate urges.'' Retrieved on 10 March 2008.</ref> On 6 March 2008 Wang began publicizing the need to grant 24 [[Home Return Permit]] to the pro-democracy lawmakers.<ref>The standard HK. \"[http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=21&art_id=62808&sid=17985905&con_type=1&d_str=20080310&sear_year=2008 The standard HK] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522061048/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=21&art_id=62808&sid=17985905&con_type=1&d_str=20080310&sear_year=2008 |date=2011-05-22 }}\". ''Wang in Big step on home permits''. Retrieved 10 March 2008.</ref><ref name=\"shk2\">The standard HK. \"[http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=11&art_id=62616&sid=17926690&con_type=1&d_str=20080306&sear_year=2008 The standard HK] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522061253/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=11&art_id=62616&sid=17926690&con_type=1&d_str=20080306&sear_year=2008 |date=2011-05-22 }}\". ''TV star hopes home visits can turn democrats into patriots'' Retrieved on 10 March 2008</ref>\n\n==2008 Beijing Olympics==\nWang mentioned that it was good timing to invite the democrats to enter mainland China in time for the [[2008 Beijing Olympics]].<ref name=\"shk2\" />\n\n{{cquote|\"''[[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference|CPPCC]] chairman [[Jia Qinglin]] said we should unite people from different sectors \u2013 why not include the democrats as well?''<ref name=\"shk2\" />|20px|20px|Liza Wang tries to unite the opposing Democrats and Pro-Beijing side in Hong Kong.}}\n\nThe [[Pro-Beijing camp|Pro-Beijing party]] [[Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong]] member [[Tam Yiu Chung]] responded that the Olympics was not a good reason for changing what the central government used to do. {{Citation needed|date=May 2009}} Her concerns baffled her colleagues in the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]].<ref name=\"shk1\" /> Democrat member [[Albert Ho]] said the issue of a home visit permit was such a rightful thing. It has never been mentioned by any politician but a performer. He appreciates Wang's efforts.<ref name=\"shk2\" /> Wang is a member, but not a standing committee member of the CPPCC.\n\n==Community work==\nAs a mainstay at the [[TVB]] television network, Wang has gained almost legendary status for her efforts not merely as an entertainer but also as a philanthropist with a heart for social works and for improving lives in rural [[People's Republic of China|China]] and other areas. Within Hong Kong, she has also been a [[Masters of Ceremonies|MC]] hosting TVB [[telethon]]s for [[Tung Wah Group of Hospitals]] and many other charities.\n\nWang, being a two time cancer survivor (first [[thyroid cancer|thyroid]] then breast cancer), she decided to be an executive committee member of the Hong Kong Anti-Cancer Society.<ref name=\"cityu\" /> A series of informative radio talk shows on [[Radio Television Hong Kong|RTHK]] was also hosted where medical specialists were invited to discuss the many types of cancer. She has helped raised charities, awareness and fundings for cancer patients. Recently a free concert was given at [[Tin Shui Wai]] for 4,500 residents; the concert was filled to capacity and hundreds were turned away. The crowd prevented guest performers like [[Miriam Yeung]] and [[Denise Ho]] from arriving on time. Denise Ho ascribed the audience overflow to Wang's popularity.<ref name=\"xinhua1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nLiza Wang was married during the height of her career to a businessman Lau Cheong-wah (\u5289\u660c\u83ef) in December 1971. Due to her busy life she became a deficit wife and the marriage ended in divorce in 1983, but they are still remained good friends. In the late 1980s, she met [[Law Kar-ying]], openly acknowledged as her partner for over twenty years, and whom she married on 2 May 2009 in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New bride: 61-year-old Liza Wang |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/showbiz/2009-05/06/content_7748935.htm |work=[[China Daily]]|date=5 May 2009|accessdate=7 May 2009}}</ref> Being a native [[Shanghainese]], Wang speaks fluent Shanghainese and has always identified as a Shanghainese.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0wsWxUXbE_U</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#B0C4DE\" align=\"center\"\n|+ '''Television series'''\n! Year !! Title !! Role \n|-\n| 1974 || ''[[Eternal Spring (TV series)|Eternal Spring]]''<br>\u300a[[:zh:\u6c38\u6046\u7684\u6625\u5929 (1974\u5e74\u96fb\u8996\u5287)|\u6c38\u6046\u7684\u6625\u5929]]\u300b||Mao Yuin Yuin<br>\u6bdb\u5713\u5713\n|-\n| 1975 || ''[[The Golden Chrysanthemum (TV series)|The Golden Chrysanthemum]]''<br>\u300a[[:zh:\u91d1\u8449\u83ca (1975\u5e74\u96fb\u8996\u5287)|\u91d1\u8449\u83ca]]\u300b||Zhau Yuk Sin<br>\u5468\u7389\u4ed9\n|-\n| 1975 || ''[[Lady with the Lute (TV series)|Lady with the Lute]]''<br>\u300a[[:zh:\u8d99\u4e94\u5a18 (1975\u5e74\u96fb\u8996\u5287)|\u8d99\u4e94\u5a18]]\u300b||Zhiu Ng Niong<br>\u8d99\u4e94\u5a18\n|-\n| 1975 || ''[[Legend of the Purple Hairpin (TV series)|Legend of the Purple Hairpin]]''<br>\u300a[[:zh:\u7d2b\u91f5\u8a18 (1975\u5e74\u96fb\u8996\u5287)|\u7d2b\u91f5\u8a18]]\u300b||Fok Siu Yuk<br>\u970d\u5c0f\u7389\n|-\n| 1976 || ''[[The Legend of the Book and the Sword (1976 TV series)|The Legend of the Book and the Sword]]''<br>\u300a[[:zh:\u66f8\u528d\u6069\u4ec7\u9304 (1976\u5e74\u96fb\u8996\u5287)|\u66f8\u528d\u6069\u4ec7\u9304]]\u300b || Fok-ching-tung<br>\u970d\u9752\u6850 \n|-\n| 1977 || ''[[A House Is Not a Home (TV series)|A House Is Not a Home]]''<br>\u300a[[:zh:\u5bb6\u8b8a (1977\u5e74\u96fb\u8996\u5287)|\u5bb6\u8b8a]]\u300b||Lok Lam<br>\u6d1b\u7433\n|-\n| 1979 || ''[[Over the Rainbow (1979 TV series)|Over the Rainbow]]''<br>\u300a[[:zh:\u5929\u8679 (\u96fb\u8996\u5287)|\u5929\u8